<DOC><DOCNO> AP880317-0041 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 0451EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w BC-Iran-Contra-Thumbnails     03-17 0445</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Iran-Contra-Thumbnails,440</SECOND><HEAD>With PM-Iran-Contra Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here are brief sketches of the men indicted bya federal grand jury Wednesday on charges stemming from theIran-Contra affair.</TEXT><HEAD>OLIVER L. NORTH</HEAD><TEXT>   North, a Marine lieutenant colonel, is a former member of theNational Security Council staff. He played the central role insupervising the arms shipments to Iran and in helping coordinateassistance to the Nicaraguan rebels during the 1985-86 period whenCongress barred U.S. government aid for the rebels.   He was fired from his NSC post in November 1986 when theIran-Contra affair first became public.   Born in San Antonio, Texas, North, 44, was raised in Philmont,N.Y. He graduated from the U.S. Naval Academy, where he was aboxing champion. He received numerous medals for heroism in theVietnam War. North and his wife, Betsy, have four children. Helives in Great Falls, Va.</TEXT><HEAD>JOHN M. POINDEXTER</HEAD><TEXT>   Poindexter, a retired rear admiral, had a lifelong career withthe Navy. Born in Odom, Ind., Poindexter, 51, received a Ph.D innuclear physics from California Institute of Technology in 1964.   He joined the National Security Council staff in June 1981 as amilitary assistant, succeeding Robert C. McFarlane as PresidentReagan's national security adviser in December 1985. Earlier in hiscareer he was on the personal staff of three Navy secretaries andwas the top assistant to the chief of naval operations.   His wife, Linda, is an ordained Episcopal priest. They have fivesons.</TEXT><HEAD>RICHARD V. SECORD</HEAD><TEXT>   Secord, 55, a retired major general in the Air Force, spentvirtually his entire career in the military. A native of LaRue,Ohio, Secord graduated from West Point. He was one of the firstAmerican combat pilots in Vietnam. Early in his career, he also ranbombing missions for the CIA from Laos. He resigned from the AirForce in 1983 after federal investigators looked into hisrelationship with former CIA agent Edwin Wilson, who was convictedof selling weapons to Libya.   Secord and his business associate, Albert Hakim, were the twomost prominent figures among the clandestine operators who assistedNorth in supplying the Nicaraguan Contras.</TEXT><HEAD>ALBERT HAKIM</HEAD><TEXT>   Hakim, 51, a naturalized American born in Iran, is a businessmanbased in Los Gatos, Calif. Hakim left Iran for good in 1978 whenthe shah of Iran was forced from power. In the mid-1970s, Hakim metSecord in Tehran; the two later became business partners.   Hakim travels frequently, rarely staying in the same place forlong. His second wife was born in South Korea. Investigators sayHakim was the money man who handled the accounts and financialarrangements in the Iran-Contra affair.</TEXT></DOC>